<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="starch-cellulose-structure-function">Starch &amp; Cellulose: Structure &amp; Function</h2><h4 id="starch">Starch</h4><ul><li><p>Starch is the <b>storage</b> polysaccharide of <b>plants</b></p></li><li><p>It is stored as granules in plastids (e.g. chloroplasts) and amyloplasts (small, membrane bound organelles containing starch granules)</p></li><li><p>Due to starch molecules being large <b>polymers</b> consisting of thousands of <b>glucose monomers</b>, starch takes <b>longer to digest </b>than glucose</p></li><li><p>Starch is constructed from <b>two</b> <b>different</b> polysaccharides:</p><ul><li><p><b>Amylose</b> (10 - 30% of starch)</p><ul><li><p><b>Unbranched</b> helix-shaped chain with <b>1,4 glycosidic bonds</b> between <b>α-glucose</b> molecules</p></li><li><p>The helix shape enables it to be more compact and thus it is more resistant to digestion</p></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Starch and Glycogen_ Amylose" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="698" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose_1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylose.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Amylose - one of the two polysaccharides present in starch</b></i></p><ul><li><p><b>Amylopectin</b> (70 - 90% of starch)</p><ul><li><p>1,4 glycosidic bonds between α-glucose molecules (as found in amylose)<b> but also 1,6 glycosidic bonds</b> form between glucose molecules creating a <b>branched</b> molecule</p></li><li><p>The branches result in many terminal glucose molecules that can be <b>easily hydrolysed</b> for use during <b>cellular respiration </b>or added to for storage</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Starch and Glycogen_ Amylopectin" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1009" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin_1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Starch-and-Glycogen_-Amylopectin.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Amylopectin - the other polysaccharide present in starch</b></i></p><ul><li><p><b>Starch</b> is a storage polysaccharide because it is:</p><ul><li><p><b>Compact</b> (so large quantities can be stored)</p></li><li><p><b>Insoluble</b> (so will have <b>no osmotic effect,</b> unlike glucose which would cause water to move into cells, meaning cells would then have to have thicker cell walls to withstand the increased internal water pressure)</p></li></ul></li></ul><h4 id="cellulose-structure">Cellulose – structure</h4><ul><li><p>Cellulose is a <b>polymer</b> consisting of long chains of <b>β-glucose</b> joined together by <b>1,4 glycosidic bonds</b></p></li><li><p>As β-glucose is an <span class="popovers" data-content="Organic molecules that have the same molecular formula but different structures which results in different properties." data-title="Isomer" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">isomer</span> of α-glucose, consecutive β-glucose molecules must be <b>rotated 180° to each other</b> in order to form the 1,4 glycosidic bonds</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="2.2.1 Formation of Sugars 1" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="333" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2022/01/2.2.1-Formation-of-Sugars-1.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>To form the 1,4 glycosidic bond between two β-glucose molecules, the glucose molecules must be rotated to 180° to each other</b></i></p><ul><li><p>Due to the <b>inversion</b> of the β-glucose molecules <b>many</b> <b>hydrogen</b> <b>bonds</b> form between the long chains, giving cellulose it’s great <b>strength</b></p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Cellulose_ hydrogen bond formation between chains" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="691" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/12/Cellulose_-hydrogen-bond-formation-between-chains.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Cellulose is used as a structural component due to the strength it has from the many hydrogen bonds that form between the long chains of β-glucose molecules</b></i></p><h4 id="cellulose-function">Cellulose – function</h4><ul><li><p>Cellulose is the <b>main structural component </b>of <b>cell walls</b> due to its strength, which is a result of the many hydrogen bonds found between the parallel chains of <b>microfibrils</b></p></li><li><p>The <b>high tensile strength</b> of cellulose allows it to be <b>stretched without breaking </b>which makes it possible for cell walls to withstand <b>turgor pressure</b></p></li><li><p>The cellulose fibres and other molecules (e.g. lignin) found in the <b>cell wall</b> form a matrix which increases the strength of the cell walls</p></li><li><p>These <b>strengthened cell walls</b> provide <b>support</b> to plants</p></li></ul></div></div></div>